    <string name="audio_transport_flash_example">The lamp keepers unseal the old star chart</string>
    <string name="audio_transport_pro_hint">pro only supports ASCII input.</string>
    <string name="audio_transport_pro_example">BELLS MARK THE FIRST WATCH</string>
    <string name="audio_transport_ultra_hint">ultra is for UTF-8 text.</string>
    <string name="audio_transport_ultra_example">The lamp keepers unseal the old star chart</string>
    <string name="audio_sample_thematic_2">Deep in the bell tower, the sealed engine begins to hum</string>
    <string name="audio_sample_thematic_3">The seventh lamp is lit, yet the far gate stays silent</string>
    <string name="audio_sample_thematic_4">Beyond the ash harbor, a pilgrim vessel crosses the black water</string>
    <string name="audio_sample_thematic_5">When the iron bells answer, the outer lock still holds</string>
    <string name="audio_sample_thematic_long_1">The bell tower ledger states that the east furnace answered before dawn, well before the roof lamps were due to rise. Three attendants turned the brass wheels by hand while soot drifted from the upper vents and settled across the steps. From behind the sealed hatch came a low, steady hum, held so long that the night clerks began tapping its measure into wax tablets. When the last note thinned away, no one touched the iron latch, yet every witness signed the same line: the machine below had woken of its own accord.</string>
    <string name="audio_sample_thematic_long_2">At second watch the gatehouse lamps were trimmed, the outer bolts were tested again, and soot was scraped from the chain hinges. No signal came from the far corridor, but the stone floor kept trembling in short intervals, as though a heavy drive beneath the hall had resumed an unfinished labor. The wardens counted each tremor against the water clock and found the pattern returned whenever the western wall took the full weight of the wind. Before the watch was dismissed, fresh wax was pressed over the inner lock, and the report closed with a warning that the silence beyond the gate was now an occupied silence.</string>
    <string name="audio_sample_thematic_long_3">The furnace chronicle records that the red lamps were raised one by one until the whole chamber glowed like banked coals behind smoke. When the final chain fell still, the signal clerks copied each pulse into wax tablets while the upper galleries answered with the scrape of iron hooks. Four slow returns came back through the rafters, each weaker than the last, yet none of the recorders agreed on which wall had carried the voice. The closing line notes that the bells were left unwound until dawn, because no one in the chamber wished to hear what might answer a fifth call.</string>
    <string name="audio_sample_thematic_long_4">A voyage record from the ash coast tells of a night crossing under a broken moon and a sky dimmed by furnace dust. The hull lamps were hooded, the chart room kept silent, and only the slow pulse of the engine sanctum marked the hours below deck. Near midnight the helmsman ordered the prow turned three degrees after pale shapes were seen moving between the black swells, though no sound ever reached the rail. By morning the vessel found the harbor lights again, and the final entry says every lamp was rekindled in thanks except the one beside the sealed coffer.</string>
    <string name="audio_sample_pro_2">SEAL THE OUTER LOCK</string>
    <string name="audio_sample_pro_3">COPPER WARDENS STIR THE DRIVE</string>
    <string name="audio_sample_pro_4">SEVENTH LAMP LIT GATE STILL SILENT</string>
    <string name="audio_sample_pro_5">HOLD FORMATION BELOW IRON MASTS</string>
    <string name="audio_sample_pro_long_1">BELL TOWER LEDGER. EAST FURNACE ANSWERED BEFORE DAWN. THREE ATTENDANTS TURNED THE BRASS WHEELS BY HAND WHILE SOOT FELL THROUGH THE UPPER VENTS. A LOW STEADY HUM CAME THROUGH THE SEALED HATCH. FINAL LINE STATES THE MACHINE BELOW WOKE OF ITS OWN ACCORD.</string>
    <string name="audio_sample_pro_long_2">SECOND WATCH REPORT. GATEHOUSE LAMPS TRIMMED, OUTER BOLTS TESTED AGAIN, CHAIN HINGES SCRAPED CLEAN. NO SIGNAL CAME FROM THE FAR CORRIDOR, BUT THE FLOOR KEPT SHAKING IN SHORT INTERVALS ABOVE THE DRIVE HALL. FRESH WAX WAS PRESSED OVER THE INNER LOCK BEFORE DISMISSAL.</string>
    <string name="audio_sample_pro_long_3">FURNACE CHRONICLE. RED LAMPS RAISED ONE BY ONE UNTIL THE CHAMBER GLOWED THROUGH THE SMOKE. SIGNAL CLERKS COPIED EACH PULSE INTO WAX TABLETS WHILE IRON HOOKS SCRAPED IN THE UPPER GALLERIES. FOUR SLOW RETURNS CAME BACK. BELLS LEFT UNWOUND UNTIL DAWN.</string>
    <string name="audio_sample_pro_long_4">ASH COAST VOYAGE. HULL LAMPS HOODED, CHART ROOM SILENT, ENGINE SANCTUM MARKING THE HOURS BELOW DECK. PROW TURNED THREE DEGREES AFTER PALE SHAPES MOVED BETWEEN THE BLACK SWELLS. HARBOR LIGHTS RETURNED AT DAWN. ONE LAMP BESIDE THE SEALED COFFER STAYED DARK.</string>

